\textbf{Answer:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Fish 1: \textbf{dies}
    \item Fish 2: \textbf{survives}
    \item Fish 3: \textbf{survives}
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Reasoning:}

Because of the ``gate'' rule --- fish $i+1$ can only eat fish $i$ after $i$ has eaten $i-1$ --- the only way any eating can start is if fish $2$ eats fish $1$.

We ask: if $2$ eats $1$, will $3$ then eat $2$? Fish $3$ would only do that if it were safe from fish $4$.  

Work backwards from the top of the chain:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Fish $10000$ has no predator, so if enabled it would eat fish $9999$.
    \item Therefore, fish $9999$ will avoid eating $9998$ (to avoid being eaten by $10000$).
    \item This reasoning propagates downward in an alternating pattern: $9998$ would eat $9997$, $9997$ would avoid $9996$, and so on.
\end{itemize}

Tracing this alternation shows that fish $4$ would eat fish $3$ if $3$ ever ate $2$. Hence $3$ will \emph{not} eat $2$.  

Knowing this, fish $2$ sees it is safe to eat fish $1$. Once $1$ is eaten, no further eating is possible.

\textbf{Conclusion:} Fish $1$ dies, while fish $2$ and fish $3$ survive.

\medskip\n\textbf{Generalization:} With an even total number of fish, only fish $1$ gets eaten; with an odd total, no fish eats at all.

Let \Sigma \subset S^{3} = \partial B^{4} be a smooth, closed, orientable, connected surface. Denote the two components of $S^{3} \setminus \Sigma$ by $X$ and $Y$.

\textbf{Step 1 (Compress on one side until spheres).}
Because $S^{3}$ contains no closed incompressible surfaces of positive genus, $\Sigma$ is compressible in $X$. Choose a \emph{maximal} collection $\Delta$ of pairwise disjoint compressing disks for $\Sigma$ in $X$. Compress $\Sigma$ along all disks of $\Delta$. The result $\Sigma_{\Delta}$ is incompressible in the compressed manifold $X_{\Delta}$, hence every component of $\Sigma_{\Delta}$ is a 2--sphere. Since $S^{3}$ is irreducible, each such sphere bounds a 3--ball in $X_{\Delta}$ (and thus in $X$).

Equivalently, $X$ is obtained from a (possibly disconnected) union $B$ of 3--balls by attaching 1--handles; the attaching curves on $\partial B$ are the circles $\partial\Delta$, and adding those tubes to $\partial B$ recovers $\Sigma$.

\textbf{Step 2 (Push into $B^{4}$ and take the dual picture).}
Give $S^{3}$ a collar in $B^{4}$, $S^{3} \times [0,\varepsilon] \subset B^{4}$. Push the interior of each 3--ball of $B$ slightly into $B^{4}$ (so each becomes a 0--handle properly embedded in $B^{4}$), and for each tube used above attach a standard 1--handle in the collar with core an arc parallel to the corresponding co--core in $X$. Because the compressing disks were disjoint, these 1--handles can be chosen disjoint.

Let $H \subset B^{4}$ be the resulting 3--manifold. By construction:
\begin{itemize}
    \item $H$ has a handle decomposition with only 0-- and 1--handles, hence $H$ is a (3--dimensional) handlebody, i.e. a boundary connected sum of solid tori (a regular neighborhood of a properly embedded graph).
    \item The boundary of $H$ on $\partial B^{4} = S^{3}$ is precisely the surface obtained from $\partial B$ by adding the tubes dual to $\Delta$, i.e. it is $\Sigma$.
\end{itemize}

Since $\Sigma$ is connected, the underlying graph is connected, so $H$ is a connected handlebody. Its genus equals $g(\Sigma)$.

Thus every smoothly embedded closed orientable connected surface in $S^{3}$ bounds a 3--dimensional handlebody in $B^{4}$. $\qed$

\emph{Remarks.}
\begin{itemize}
    \item If one prefers, one can pick $\Delta$ nonseparating of size $g(\Sigma)$, yielding a single 3--ball and $g$ 1--handles, so $H \cong \#^{\,g}(S^{1} \times D^{2})$.
    \item Conceptually, this is the ``movie'' that $\Sigma$ is obtained from a sphere by a sequence of ambient 1--surgeries; thickening the movie in the time direction gives a 3--dimensional cobordism made only of 0-- and 1--handles.
\end{itemize}

