Label the figures by $1$ to $9$, from left to right, then from top to bottom. We claim that each of Figures $2,4,6,7,8,9$ can be deformed to another figure, but each of Figures $1,3,5$ cannot.

The band type of a band is determined by the type of the core knot together with the framing of the band (which takes value in $\tfrac12\mathbb Z$). One can check that the cores of the bands have types:
\begin{itemize}
\item Unknot: Figures $1,2,5,7,8,9$;
\item Left-handed trefoil: Figure $3$;
\item Right-handed trefoil: Figures $4,6$.
\end{itemize}

The two right-handed trefoil each has framing $+3$, hence $\{4,6\}$ forms an equivalence class.

The framings of the unknots are given by:
\begin{itemize}
\item $-1/2$: Figures $8,9$;
\item $0$: Figure $5$;
\item $+1/2$: Figure $1$;
\item $+1$: Figures $2,7$.
\end{itemize}
Hence $\{2,7\}$ and $\{8,9\}$ each form an equivalence class.

The rest singletons $1,3,5$ each form an equivalence class.
